Date: Thu 30 Nov 2000 07:47:11 -0500
From: M. Hoeber <mhoeber@winstar.com>
Source: Internews (Arusha), Tue 28 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200011280111.html >

East African Community Meeting to Discuss Ebola Outbreak
--------------------------------------------------------
ARUSHA: The East African Community (EAC) partners Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania have convened an urgent meeting of health experts to assess the
spread of Ebola hemorrhagic fever for 2 days beginning Thu 30 Nov 2000 in
Arusha. Ebola hemorrhagic fever has already killed 120 out of 340 people
confirmed to have contracted the deadly disease in Gulu, Uganda over the
past 3 months. Of the first 31 victims, 3 were student nurses who treated
Ebola patients in Gull's Lacor Hospital. Dr. Nyamajeje Weggoro, a senior
EAC official, told Internews that the meeting would chart out a common
strategy on how to combat the deadly disease. "The main thrust is to
assess the spread of Ebola in the region and the possible sources of the
disease beyond the EA borders," Dr. Weggoro said. He said the meeting
would put in place common measures to curb Ebola's spread from Uganda to
the other 2 member countries. The ECA official also said the experts would
discuss how to mobilize local and foreign resources required to contain the
disease.
Fears of cross-border infections between Uganda and Kenya arose last week
when Ugandan health authorities informed their Kenyan counterparts that at
least 7 Kenyans had attended the funeral of an Ebola fever victim across
the border and therefore could have come into contact with the killer
virus. Tanzanian health authorities reported 5 suspected cases in the
Mwanza, Kagera and Dar es Salaam regions with symptoms of the killer
disease on 22 Nov 2000, but said that there "was no conclusive evidence to
confirm Ebola virus infection." "Tanzania is taking the cases very
seriously until it is proved otherwise," Mariam Mwafisi, Permanent
Secretary in the Health Ministry, said.
--
Martha Hoeber
M&P Analyst
