[2
Date: Thu 30 Nov 2000 07:45:08 -0500
From: M. Hoeber <mhoeber@winstar.com>
Source: The Monitor (Kampala), Wed 29 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200011290045.html>

Parliament Demands Compensation for Nurses
------------------------------------------
KAMPALA: A total of 6 nurses in Lacor Hospital, Gulu, have died from Ebola
hemorrhagic fever in the last 10 days, bringing to 10 the number of deaths
[among nurses since the epidemic began on 13 Oct 2000. A highly-placed
medical source said hospital staff went on strike last Wednesday because of
the new deaths, but the stoppage was called off after a closed meeting with
Ministry of Health officials.
At a Press Conference in Kampala yesterday, Assistant Commissioner of
Health Services, Dr. Alex Opio, said he could neither confirm nor deny
figures of nurses' deaths. But he said 10 nurses had died since the
disease broke out. An inter-ministerial Ebola Task Force is examining the
nurses' deaths and the possibility of compensation. "The Task Force is to
act within the laws governing the profession," Opio said. The nurses are
among 28 people whose deaths, apparently from Ebola fever, have been
recorded in Gulu since 18 Nov 2000. Between 24 Nov 2000 and 27 Nov 2000
alone, 15 people died in Gulu and another in Masindi, according to the
Ministry. "The number is unacceptable to us and we are doing everything to
bring it down," Opio said yesterday. Just when health officials were
confident that the situation was under control, some of the highest figures
in a single week have been reported, though Masindi and Mbarara reported no
new cases or deaths in the last 24 hours. The overall death toll is set at
149 out of 367 cases. A total of 26 patients remain hospitalized.
Meanwhile, the Chairman of the Parliamentary Committee on Social Services,
Dr. Timothy Mutesasira, has demanded that the Workman's Compensation Law
apply to the nurses who died of Ebola fever. Minister of State for Health,
Beatrice Wabudeya, and other ministry officials were meeting the Committee
to discuss a bill for the establishment of the Health Services Commission,
2000. Wabudeya said she is consulting with the Solicitor General on how
the law relates to the deceased nurses.
Dr. Sam Zaramba said the new deaths were due to laxity by health workers,
lack of logistics due to unfulfilled pledges, and cultural habits. He
discouraged newly-discharged people from engaging in sex, arguing that
tests had found semen to contain the Ebola virus after 21 days.
[Byline: Carolyne Nakazibwe & Katamba G. Mohammed
