Date: Thu 30 Nov 2000 16:06:33 +0100
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail>
Source: WHO Disease Outbreaks Report, Thu 30 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://www.who.int/disease-outbreak-news>

Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever in Uganda - WHO Update 32
--------------------------------------------------
As of Wed 29 Nov 2000, the Ugandan Ministry of Health has reported
cumulative figures for Gulu district of 354 cases and 140 deaths.
The mobile teams in Gulu district are intensifying disease control
activities and focusing particularly on areas where there has been recent
disease activity. They are tracing and closely following up contacts of
the most recent laboratory confirmed cases, as well as continuing
case-finding activities in the district. Additional activities have been
initiated to enhance public health education in Gulu district. Messages
and discussions about the disease will continue on the radio and in film
shows, with new drama and musical events planned to further increase the
level of awareness about the disease.
A total of 5 suspected cases was reported from Tanzania. These cases were
investigated and clinical samples sent to the National Institute for
Virology, South Africa. The preliminary results for all cases are negative.
WHO recommends no special restrictions on travel or trade to or from
Uganda. Many countries have routine health regulations concerning travel
and trade. No specific measures with respect to Ebola hemorrhagic fever
are warranted or advised.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The statistics released by WHO represent laboratory-confirmed cases and
deaths and take precedence over the sometimes conflicting figures emanating
from local and regional health officials. The suspected cases in Tanzania
have proved negative, and there is still no evidence that the disease has
spread beyond the Gulu neighborhood, apart from the so-far-contained small
outbreaks in Masindi and Mbarara. - Mod.CP
